salon   

sa·lon [sə lón, sa láwN]
(plural sa·lons) 
noun 
1.  grand sitting room: an elegantly furnished room in a large house where guests are received and entertained  
2.  social gathering of intellectuals: a regular gathering of prominent people from the worlds of literature, art, music, or politics, especially one held at the home of a wealthy woman. 
Salons were especially popular in the 17th, 18th, and 19th centuries. 
3.  place for hairdressing or beauty treatments: a commercial establishment where hairdressers or beauticians work, sometimes part of a larger store or a hotel  
4.  fashion expensive clothes shop: a shop selling elegant or fashionable women’s clothes, especially expensive designer clothes  
5.  arts art exhibition or gallery: an art exhibition, especially one devoted to the work of living artists, or the hall in which the exhibits are displayed  


[Late 17th century. Via French from Italian salone “large hall,” from sala , ultimately from prehistoric Germanic.]
